Over 800 young people who have completed the Bronze standard of the Duke of Edinburgh’s International Award from 76 participating schools in Lagos State will be honoured from June 28 to 30. A statement by Oshoke J. Bello, National Director of the  International Award for Young People Nigeria, organisers of the award, indicated that the event for Education District II, Education District III and Education District IV will hold on June 28 at the New Era Girls Senior Secondary School, Surulere by 12.00 noon. On June 29, the presentation for Education District I and Education District VI will hold at the Government Senior College, Agege by 12:00noon. The event for Education District V will take place on June 30, at the Awori Ajeromi Senior Grammar School, Agboju by 1pm   How Southeast governors frustrated Igbo president, by…     Why Peter Obi can’t be president, by Mbaka     Sanwo-Olu, NCC, others review ease of doing business   The Duke of Edinburgh’s International Award is a global non-formal education framework which challenges young people to discover their potential and find their purpose, passion and place. Since 1956, millions of young people have taken part in the award in more than 130 countries and territories. The Duke of Edinburgh’s International Award Foundation drives and supports the award’s global growth, so more young people can take part. In Nigeria, The Duke of Edinburgh’s International Award operates under the name The International Award for Young People Nigeria. The trustees of the award in Nigeria are: one-time Lagos State Commissioner for Finance Olawale Edun; Dr. Doyinsola Abiola; Mrs. Daniella A. Uijlenhoed; Mrs. Folake Fawunmi; Mr. Abdulrahman Sambo; and Mrs. Efunike Animashawun.